# Quiz Game (with Multiple-Choice Questions) ‚Äì C Program
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This C program is a simple quiz game that asks the user multiple-choice questions and keeps score.  
It‚Äôs perfect for beginners learning conditional statements, loops, arrays, and basic input/output in C.  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# FEATURES
1. Asks a series of MCQ questions  
2. Accepts answers and checks correctness  
3. Displays final score  
4. Easy to extend with more questions  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# STEPS
1. Copy the code into a file named `quiz_game.c`  
2. Compile it using a C compiler (e.g., `gcc quiz_game.c -o quiz_game`)  
3. Run the program using `./quiz_game` or `quiz_game.exe`  
4. Answer the questions by entering the option (A, B, C, D)  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# CODE
#include <stdio.h>
#include <ctype.h>

struct Question {
    char question[256];
    char options[4][100];
    char correctOption;
};

int main() {
    struct Question quiz[] = {
        {
            "What is the capital of France?",
            { "A. Paris", "B. London", "C. Rome", "D. Berlin" },
            'A'
        },
        {
            "Which language is used for system programming?",
            { "A. HTML", "B. Python", "C. C", "D. Java" },
            'C'
        },
        {
            "Who is the father of C Language?",
            { "A. Dennis Ritchie", "B. Bjarne Stroustrup", "C. James Gosling", "D. Guido van Rossum" },
            'A'
        },
        {
            "What is the value of PI (approx)?",
            { "A. 3.12", "B. 3.14", "C. 3.18", "D. 3.20" },
            'B'
        },
        {
            "Which of the following is a loop structure in C?",
            { "A. if", "B. switch", "C. while", "D. goto" },
            'C'
        }
    };

    int totalQuestions = sizeof(quiz) / sizeof(quiz[0]);
    int score = 0;
    char answer;

    printf("\nüìò Welcome to the C Quiz Game!\n");
    printf("Enter the correct option (A/B/C/D) for each question.\n\n");

    for (int i = 0; i < totalQuestions; i++) {
        printf("Q%d: %s\n", i + 1, quiz[i].question);
        for (int j = 0; j < 4; j++) {
            printf("%s\n", quiz[i].options[j]);
        }

        printf("Your answer: ");
        scanf(" %c", &answer);
        answer = toupper(answer);

        if (answer == quiz[i].correctOption) {
            printf("‚úÖ Correct!\n\n");
            score++;
        } else {
            printf("‚ùå Wrong! Correct answer: %c\n\n", quiz[i].correctOption);
        }
    }

    printf("üéâ Quiz Completed! Your Score: %d/%d\n", score, totalQuestions);

    if (score == totalQuestions) {
        printf("üèÜ Excellent! You got all answers right!\n");
    } else if (score >= totalQuestions / 2) {
        printf("üëç Good job! Keep practicing.\n");
    } else {
        printf("üìò Keep learning! Try again.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Usage Tips
- Questions can be added easily by appending to the `quiz[]` array  
- You can add a timer, difficulty levels, or categories for more engagement  
- To handle hundreds of questions, use file reading or a database  
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
